## Image Provenance Systems for Medical Context Verification: Technical Assessment and Integration Pathways for MedContext

### Executive Summary

The PBS article references the **News Provenance Project**, a 2019-2020 proof-of-concept collaboration between The New York Times and IBM that explored blockchain-based image provenance tracking for journalism. While this project itself does not constitute a publicly accessible medical image provenance database, it catalyzed the development of **C2PA (Coalition for Content Provenance and Authenticity)**—an open, industry-standard specification that offers a viable technical foundation for medical image verification. [pbs](https://www.pbs.org/newshour/science/out-of-context-photos-are-a-powerful-low-tech-form-of-misinformation)

**Key Finding**: No dedicated medical image provenance database with public API access currently exists. However, C2PA provides open-source SDKs and specifications that could be adapted for medical imaging contexts, representing a significant opportunity for the MedContext project to pioneer healthcare applications of content provenance technology.

### The News Provenance Project: Origin and Evolution

#### Project Overview

The News Provenance Project emerged in 2019 as a research initiative by The New York Times R&D team in partnership with IBM Garage to combat visual misinformation. The project addressed a critical vulnerability: authentic photographs being stripped of context, selectively cropped, or presented with misleading captions as they circulate across digital platforms. [brown.columbia](https://brown.columbia.edu/news-provenance-project/)

#### Technical Architecture

The system employed **Hyperledger Fabric**, an open-source blockchain framework, to create an immutable ledger storing photographic metadata including: [brown.columbia](https://brown.columbia.edu/news-provenance-project/)

- Date and location of image capture
- Original publisher and photographer
- Camera specifications and settings
- Publishing history across multiple outlets
- Editing provenance (cropping, enhancement, modifications)

The blockchain architecture enabled multiple news organizations to share a distributed repository of image provenance without relying on a centralized trusted authority. A browser extension prototype demonstrated how this metadata could be surfaced to social media users, displaying trust signals directly in Twitter feeds. [spec.c2pa](https://spec.c2pa.org/specifications/specifications/1.0/guidance/Guidance.html)

#### Current Status and Limitations

The News Provenance Project concluded as a proof-of-concept in late 2019-early 2020. The project did not evolve into a sustained public database or API service. Key limitations included: [tbray](https://www.tbray.org/ongoing/When/202x/2025/09/18/C2PA-Investigations)

- **Scalability challenges**: Perceptual hashing for image matching proved inadequate when images underwent resolution changes or platform-specific transformations
- **Adoption barriers**: Blockchain infrastructure required buy-in from multiple stakeholders and integration with existing publishing workflows
- **Specificity to journalism**: Architecture optimized for news photography rather than medical imaging workflows
- **No medical imaging focus**: Zero evidence of DICOM support, clinical metadata, or healthcare-specific provenance tracking

### C2PA: The Industry Standard for Content Provenance

#### Technical Specification

C2PA (Coalition for Content Provenance and Authenticity) represents the maturation of concepts explored in the News Provenance Project into a comprehensive technical standard. The C2PA specification defines how to create **Content Credentials**—cryptographically-signed manifests embedded directly into media files. [blog.cloudflare](https://blog.cloudflare.com/preserve-content-credentials-with-cloudflare-images/)

A C2PA manifest contains: [c2pa](https://c2pa.org/specifications/specifications/2.3/specs/C2PA_Specification.html)

- **Creator information**: Identity of individual or organization that created the asset
- **Capture details**: Device model, serial number, sensor data, GPS coordinates, timestamp
- **Editing history**: Complete chain of modifications with timestamps and software used
- **AI involvement**: Disclosure of generative AI tools used in creation or editing
- **Assertions**: Custom metadata relevant to specific use cases (copyright, licensing, content restrictions)

Each manifest is cryptographically signed using X.509 certificates, creating a tamper-evident seal. If the asset is modified after signing, the manifest becomes invalid unless a new manifest is added documenting the change. [opensource.contentauthenticity](https://opensource.contentauthenticity.org/docs/getting-started/)

#### Adoption Landscape

C2PA has achieved significant industry adoption across multiple sectors: [aws.amazon](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/ard-ensures-content-provenance-with-c2pa-and-aws/)

**Camera Manufacturers**:

